         <div type="translation">
            <p><choice corresp="#a1"><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:carling2000"/><citedRange>307, 345</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><seg type="prim_transl">collecting merits one by one, during a life of humans 120 years long, under the name of Śākymuni,</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a1 #a2"><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:carling2000"/><citedRange>85</citedRange></bibl></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a1 #a2 #a3"><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:thomas1957"/><citedRange>300</citedRange></bibl></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a1 #a2 #a3 #a4 #a5 #a6 #b1 #b2 #b3 #b4 #b5 #b6"><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:sieg1944"/><citedRange>22</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:ogihara2010"/><citedRange>170</citedRange></bibl></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a1ff"><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:thomas1969"/><citedRange>235</citedRange></bibl></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a2"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">as one having arrived in this way, Arhat, Buddha and master, having understood all the dharmas,</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a3"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">he had arisen in the world. The Arhat’s lineage and family, however, was such:</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a3ff"><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:thomas1967a"/><citedRange>62</citedRange></bibl></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a4"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">the queen named Mahāmāyā was his mother, the king named Śuddhodana [was his] father, [the one] named Rāhula [was his] son, [the one] named Āna-</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a5"><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:thomas1952"/><citedRange>49</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><seg type="prim_transl">nda [was his] servant, [and the two] named Śāriputra and Maudgalyāyana [were his] excellent pair of disciples. The Arhat, however,</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a5 #a6"><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:thomas1969c"/><citedRange>202</citedRange></bibl></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a6"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">(who at this time) redeemed the beings worthy of conversion, with [his] servant Ānanda went in the Bṛhaddytian(?) ...</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b1"><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:carling2000"/><citedRange>172, 173</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><seg type="prim_transl">...to camp at night. The Arhat, too, || In the E.-tune: || as the result of a hundred kalpas</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b2"><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:thomas1991"/><citedRange>10</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><seg type="prim_transl">of merit, had a body that had the powers of numberless Nārāyaṇa-like heroes and which by its ornaments</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b3"><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:carling2000"/><citedRange>8, 99, 253</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:thomas1954"/><citedRange>729</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><seg type="prim_transl">and marks surpassed all things worth seeing. But going from country to country it came to him to feel sickness through the wind. 1. Thereupon the Arhat Śā-</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b3 #b4"><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:thomas1983"/><citedRange>44</citedRange></bibl></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b3ff"><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:thomas1954"/><citedRange>738</citedRange></bibl></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b4"><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:thomas1983"/><citedRange>19</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><seg type="prim_transl">kymundi, the [god] of gods, the Buddha – up to this feeling of sickness, too, he had come, intending</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b4 #b5"><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:meunier2013"/><citedRange>166</citedRange></bibl></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b5"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">to do something beneficial to the world – says to Ānanda: Go, oh Ānanda [and] with the word of the Buddha speak to Bṛhaddyuti,</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b6"><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:thomas1966"/><citedRange>268</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><seg type="prim_transl">the potter: the master, the Buddha – he feels sickness through sickness of the wind – longs for warm water and sesame oil.</seg></seg></choice></p>
         </div>
         <div type="comments">
            <p><note type="philcomment">The translation is largely based on <bibl><title corresp="ref:sieg1944"/><citedRange>22-24</citedRange></bibl>, and <bibl><title corresp="ref:carlingetal2009"/></bibl>.</note><note type="remarks">The leaf number on the margin has been lost, but an unreadable number is written inside the string hole of the verso side by a different hand. Since this leaf stands in a continuous series, it actually ought to have the leaf number 83, while the leaf number inside the string hole ought to have been 74 in theory, but this number 74 is actually attested in the following (!) leaf. The combination of lost margin and deviating string-hole numbering starts in A 15 and continues until A 24.</note><note corresp="#b1" type="philcomment">The tune has 4x12 syllables, rhythm 5/7.</note></p>
