               <item n="m_translation_old">a1 collecting merits one by one, during a life of humans 120 years long, under the name of Śākymuni,
a2 as one having arrived in this way, Arhat, Buddha and master, having understood all the dharmas,
a3 he had arisen in the world. The Arhat’s lineage and family, however, was such:
a4 the queen named Mahāmāyā was his mother, the king named Śuddhodana [was his] father, [the one] named Rāhula [was his] son, [the one] named Āna-
a5 nda [was his] servant, [and the two] named Śāriputra and Maudgalyāyana [were his] excellent pair of disciples. The Arhat, however,
a6 (who at this time) redeemed the beings worthy of conversion, with [his] servant Ānanda went in the Bṛhaddytian(?) ...
b1 ...to camp at night. The Arhat, too, || In the E.-tune: || as the result of a hundred kalpas
b2 of merit, had a body that had the powers of numberless Nārāyaṇa-like heroes and which by its ornaments
b3 and marks surpassed all things worth seeing. But going from country to country it came to him to feel sickness through the wind. 1. Thereupon the Arhat Śā-
b4 kymundi, the [god] of gods, the Buddha – up to this feeling of sickness, too, he had come, intending
b5 to do something beneficial to the world – says to Ānanda: Go, oh Ānanda [and] with the word of the Buddha speak to Bṛhaddyuti,
b6 the potter: the master, the Buddha – he feels sickness through sickness of the wind – longs for warm water and sesame oil.</item>
